SIMPLE: encounter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Encounter
<hw>En*coun"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Encountered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Encountering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>encontrer</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>contre</ets> against, L. <ets>contra</ets>. See <er>Counter</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos>]</ety> <def>To come against face to face; to meet; to
confront, either by chance, suddenly, or deliberately; especially, to
meet in opposition or with hostile intent; to engage in conflict with;
to oppose; to struggle with; <as>as, to <ex>encounter</ex> a friend in
traveling; two armies <ex>encounter</ex> each other; to
<ex>encounter</ex> obstacles or difficulties, to <ex>encounter</ex>
strong evidence of a truth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then certain philosophers of the Epicureans, and of the Stoics,
<qex>encountered</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xvii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am most fortunate thus accidentally to <qex>encounter</qex>
you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encounter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Encounter
<hw>En*coun"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To meet face to face; to
have a meeting; to meet, esp. as enemies; to engage in combat; to fight;
<as>as, three armies <ex>encountered</ex> at Waterloo</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>encounter</qex> with Andronicus.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perception and judgment, employed in the investigation of all
truth, have in the first place to <qex>encounter</qex> with
particulars.</q> <rj><qau>Tatham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encounter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Encounter
<hw>En*coun"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>encontre</ets>, fr.
<ets>encontrer</ets>. See <er>Encounter</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A meeting face to face; a running against; a sudden or
incidental meeting; an interview.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To shun the <qex>encounter</qex> of the vulgar crowd.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A meeting, with hostile purpose; hence, a combat; a
battle; <as>as, a bloody <ex>encounter</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As one for . . . fierce <qex>encounters</qex> fit</q>.
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To join their dark <qex>encounter</qex> in mid-air</q>.
<rj><qau>Milton</qau></rj>.</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Contest; conflict; fight; combat; assault;
rencounter; attack; engagement; onset. See <er>Contest</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encounterer</ent>⟦br⟧
